    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i'm specifically worried about the encroachment part though. if i have a small sign or a display case that extends slightly past the planned building line into the required setback, is that usually considered a minor violation or a major issue with the city?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Encroachment, even a small one, is usually treated by the city as a potential, albeit minor, infraction. It's not usually a \"major issue\" unless it's a blatant, structural violation that compromises safety or significantly alters the intended use of the property. A tiny sign or a display case sticking out just a bit past the line is often seen as a small oversight, perhaps something a local inspector would just give a gentle warning about.\n\nIt's always best to treat it with caution, though. You can't count on the city to overlook things just because they are small. If you're dealing with a specific code, you need to know the exact measurement. Sometimes, a little bit of encroachment can lead to a fine, or worse, a formal notice requiring you to pull it back.",
